A residential academy, VidyaGyan aims to drive transformation in the country by investing in the youth and catalyzing them into future leaders. It combs all the 75 districts of Uttar Pradesh, India\xe2\x80\x99s most populated state, to identify meritorious, rural students from economically underprivileged backgrounds. Once selected the students, who would have already completed their primary schooling, are inducted to VidyaGyan in Class VI. The students spend seven years \xe2\x80\x93 from class VI to XII \xe2\x80\x93 at the school\xe2\x80\x99s residential campuses in Bulandshahr or Sitapur. The young scholars of VidyaGyan follow a carefully crafted leadership curriculum that allows them to explore their full potential.

Established in 2009 by the Shiv Nadar Foundation, the inspiration for VidyaGyan stems from the belief that high-quality education will have a positive impact on the academic and socio-economic structure of the society to a point where it can truly uplift and transform lives. VidyaGyan aims to provide the opportunities of a world-class leadership academy to the economically backward students of rural India and transform their lives using high quality school education. VidyaGyan brings students from rural India, who are potential high achievers, at par with their urban counterparts.

I recently completed this 2 part guided project: Analyzing Worldwide Box Office Revenue with Seaborn, Plotly and Python. In this project, I worked with The Movie Database(TMDB) Box Office Prediction data set. I used statistical data visualization libraries like Seaborn and Plotly to generate interactive, publication-quality graphs. The tasks which I performed in this project:- -Visualized the target distribution using the Seaborn's distplot function. -Determined how official homepages impact the revenue of the film. -Checked the distribution of languages across films to determine which language generates the highest revenue. -Created a Word Cloud to represent the common words in film titles and descriptions. -Used Plotly's scatter function to Visualize the Number of Films Per Year. -Determined how the release days impacted the revenue of the film. -Created two different plots to figure out how the runtime affects the revenue of the film. I would like to thank Snehan Kekre for mentoring throughout the project and Coursera for giving this opportunity to get my hands on these python libraries. As a member of XOresearch data science team, I developed the following products/solutions:

- An automatic ECG interpretation system. I developed an efficient and accurate deep learning model achieving near state-of-the-art results in the detection of common cardiac problems. The model was created in pure Tensorflow and then deployed as a web-service using such tools as gRPC and RabbitMQ. As a part of this project, I developed a custom Python package for ECG processing.

- An automatic speech recognition system. I developed such components as VAD (Voice Activity Detection) and speaker identification. The system was designed in a way to work well even in the presence of large amounts of background noise.

- A Real-time face detection/recognition system. The task was to provide a simple yet efficient model able to run on a laptop on 15 FPS. I used publicly available implementations of such models as MTCNN and FaceNet and did a lot of refactoring and optimization to make them efficient.

- As a part of these projects, I did a lot of basic research on generative models, model interpretability, semi-supervised learning, etc.
